text.text: Our attitude to veggies has come a long way over the last few years. We're no longer avoiding our greens or, worse, boiling them down to a mush then suffering the resulting sludge because "it's good for you". We're learning to treat them with respect, expose their flavour, and maybe even make them the star of the show.

tip.text: It's not often a venue scores so highly in both style and eco points, but this restaurant-cum-cocktail bar does just that. Cub, the brainchild of Mr Lyan (Ryan Chetiyawardana), has zero-waste techniques woven into every step of its menu. We could spend all day harking on about how they grow ingredients on site, use waste products to ferment others and only buy sustainable produce, but the real magic isn't in the method, it's in the result: an exquisite set menu, where some courses are perfectly crafted cocktails and others daintily prepared edible art. And all this in supremely cool surrounds. Did they know how good the Japanese knotweed with raw sheep’s milk would look against their marble table tops? Or how well the mustard yellow seating would complement the golden tones of a cured egg yolk? Probably, yes.

text.text:
It's not often a venue scores so highly in both style and eco points, but this restaurant-cum-cocktail bar does just that. Cub, the brainchild of Mr Lyan (Ryan Chetiyawardana), has zero-waste techniques woven into every step of its menu. And because it takes sustainability so seriously, there's hardly any meat on the menu. When we were in we spotted some chicken stock made with excess bones from the butchers, and that was it.

Instead the menu brings out the best side of its veggies, with daintily prepared, delicious concoctions.

tip.text:
Scottish-born Isaac McHale started work in a fishmongers aged 14 and has been running with it ever since. With a pretty impressive back catalogue of jobs (Noma, The Ledbury, Elystan Street), he finally opened Clove Club in 2013 after a number of experimental supper clubs testing the waters. The result? Exquisite food served in a smart but relaxed atmosphere - a space without tablecloths, where nobody hovers over you to top up your wine or pops your napkin on your lap for you (creeps.) Stripped of all the pomp and circumstance usually associated with this level of cooking (erm it's got a Michelin star so...), the food's inventiveness, flavour and presentation is allowed to shine through.

Watch as edible art comes out from the blue-tiled open kitchen, in dishes that 'make vegetables the star of the show' rather than sliding them underneath a lovely bit o' meat. Go for lunch which is the mildly cheaper option and get stuck into the five course set menu for £65 (or, if you're really treating yourself, the nine course set menu for £95). If you're in a rush but want a taste of the good life, grab a seat at the bar and a couple of bar snacks - even here flavours are drop dead gorgeous.

tip.text:
Inspired by the traditional communities of the Peruvian Andes, Andina brings some much needed colour to London's foodie scene. Stocked up on exotic superfoods and fresh British produce, the menu here makes for mighty virtuous, health conscious combinations - with plenty of veggie, vegan and gluten free options. And all in a sleek, fairly modern surrounds.

Start your day right with a nutritious smoothie, a cup of joe or a Peruvian alternative made with barley, linseed, alfalfa and quince - warm and only slightly bitter it should perk you up nicely. Their brunches are wholesome, lunches are fresh and dinners range from delicately plated ceviche to heartier street food options. A wide range of pisco cocktails will take you from 'oh this is all very lovely' to 'shall we book tickets to Peru' in no time.

Stocked up on exotic superfoods and fresh British produce, the menu here makes for mighty virtuous, health-conscious combinations - with plenty of veggie and vegan options. And all in a sleek, modern surrounds.

From beetroot ceviche, to stewed pumpkin or Peruvian corn cakes, Andina's menu does tricks with veggies that you definitely won't have thought of.

tip.text:
Another feather in Ottolenghi's cap, Rovi promises all the veg, colour and flavour of its sister restaurants but with more focus on fermentation and grilling over fire - in a huge space with plenty of natural light, red sofas and a free-standing bar in the middle. Fruit and veg comes all the way from a biodynamic farm in Sussex, and a cooperative in East London - so not too many air miles then - and waste will be reduced with nifty tricks like making vinegar out of leftover wine.

As always, Ottolenghi elevates your five-a-day with the likes of braised and smoked carrots with puffed black barley; pan-roasted cauliflower with za’atar onions; or green beans with roasted grapes. And the worthiness doesn't stop there... the bar serves up cocktails made with house shrubs and all sorts of low intervention wines from small producers. Tidy.

tip.text:
Foley’s eclectic menu is inspired by street food from around the world. Though chef Ferdinand Montoya has a strong Asian persuasion. This plenty of bao buns, kimchi, grilled fish and lots of veggie options too.

No mixologists here so don't waste your time on cocktails. Instead grab as many sharing plates as you can afford because flavour wise they are doing all the right things. Think Roasted sweet potato with miso butter and chives, celeriac bang bang noodles or crispy aubergine bao with cured onions and sriracha. And the brunch menu? It's just as original, colourful and tasty; and features bottomless booze!

text.text:
Foley’s eclectic menu is inspired by street food from around the world, but chef Ferdinand Montoya has a clear Asian persuasion. This means plenty of bao buns, kimchi, grilled fish and a whole heck of veggie options too. In fact the veg section of the menu is just as big if not bigger than the meat and fish section.

Think roasted sweet potato with miso butter and chives, celeriac bang bang noodles or stir-fried okra with sambal sauce.
